2500|$|During the New Deal {{years as}} well as the 1940s, there was much less focus on Wall Street and finance. The {{government}} clamped down on the practice of buying equities based only on credit, but these policies began to ease. From 1946 to 1947, stocks could not be purchased [...] "on margin", meaning that an investor had to pay 100% of a stock's cost without taking on any loans. But this margin requirement was reduced four times before 1960, each time stimulating a mini-rally and boosting volume, and when the Federal Reserve reduced the <b>margin</b> <b>requirements</b> from 90% to 70%. These changes made it somewhat easier for investors to buy stocks on credit. The growing national economy and prosperity led to a recovery during the 1960s, with some down years during the early 1970s {{in the aftermath of the}} Vietnam War. Trading volumes climbed; in 1967, according to Time Magazine, volume hit 7.5 million shares a day which caused a [...] "traffic jam" [...] of paper with [...] "batteries of clerks" [...] working overtime to [...] "clear transactions and update customer accounts".|$|E
