50|$|President John F. Kennedy {{was asked}} by many to address {{the public about the}} state of the economy, but he {{ultimately}} decided not to do so. Kennedy’s advisors pushed for all sorts of remedies, from reducing the <b>margin</b> <b>requirement</b> to announcing a tax cut of $5-$10 billion to holding a “fireside chat” and discussing the health of the economy. Six weeks after deciding on not taking an action, however, Kennedy reduced the <b>margin</b> <b>requirement</b> and decided on a tax cut, hoping to incentivize large, self-financing companies.|$|R
